From &quot;North Down Memories&quot; by Keith Haines (in my bookcase) &quot;three homes of rest were built in the decade following 1898&quot;. &quot;Designed by W.J. Roome&quot; &quot;They were financed by philanthropist Mr Vance&quot;. They provided a week's holday for up to 700o deprived people from Belfast. 

From an Ulster Architectural Heritage Society Gazeteer (also in my bookcase - my bookcase is HUGE.. Lol!&quot;) &quot;three detached houses at the bottom of Downshire Road facing the sea; of two an three storeys and varied designs including hipped roofs and bonnet gables.&quot;

But this gazeteer also mentions another built in Brompton Road which is a short distance ENE of these three. This makes me wonder which one this is.
